re his enthusiasm. Lincoln has lived with American Indians, knows them, and is respected by them; all this enhances his book." --William Bright, Editor, Language   "This is the most informed and insightful assessment of the best of modern Native American literature. Lincoln is sensitive to the tribal roots of this literature, so he is able to go beyond mere criticism to cultural contextualization. I found this study quite powerful in its scope, probing depth, imaginative sweep, and sensitivity of writing. Debate on the subject may well gather around Native American Renaissance for the rest of the decade." --Alfonso Ortiz (San Juan), University of New Mexico  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory. 4aIndigenous Peoples of the Americas. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh1 aLincoln, Kenneth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052005457840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035287240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520352872423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520352872/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles